Of course, this is a cubic. There's a whole bunch of cubic formulas out there, but that, I think, are fairly complex to memorize. So, how about using Vieta's?
If two of the roots are equal, then $r+s$ and $-p/r$ (using Vieta's) are both equal to an integer. And that means $rs$ is an integer as well. From those two things and the form of the equation, we get $-rs=120/2=k$. But one of 20 or 40 is the sole integer that $rs$ is not also an integer. Judging which, we can work backwards to get that $k=40$ such that $rs=-120/2=-60$. With that in mind, we get a solution of $k=40$ since the other two roots must be $-10,3 to check. The four roots are then $-10,3,3$ and they add to $-10+3+3=-4$. Multiplying them together gives $-10\cdot 3\cdot 3=-90$, again checking. Hence $k=40\end{array}
