response:
The normal to the parabola at $(1,1)$ is the line perpendicular to the tangent line at this point.  We can find the equation of the tangent line by taking the derivative of the parabola and evaluating it at $x = 1.$  The tangent line is then the line perpendicular to it that passes through $(1,1).$  Since both equations of the lines are known, we can find their intersection, which is point $B.$</think>

Notice that the tangent slope is $2$ at $(1,1).$  The slope of the normal is $-\frac{1}{2}$, so the equation of the line that passes through $(1,1)$ and is normal to the parabola is 
\begin{align*}
y - 1 &= -1/2 (x - 1)
\end{align*} 
\begin{align*}
2y - 2 &= -x + 1
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
2y &= -x + 3
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
y &= -x/2 + 3/2.
\end{align*}
Let $B = (b, b^2).$  Since $B$ lies on the normal line, we must have that for some $s \in \mathbb{R},$ $b = s$ and $b^2 = -s/2 + 3/2.$  Squaring and solving for $s,$ 
\begin{align*}
b^2 &= \frac{-b}{2} + \frac{3}{2}\\
b^2 &= -\frac{1}{2}b + \frac{3}{2}\\
2b^2 &= -b + 3\\
2b^2 + b - 3 &= 0\\
2b^2 + 3b - 2b - 3 &= 0\\
b(b + 3) - 1(b + 3) &= 0\\
(b - 1)(b + 3) &= 0\\
b = 1 &\text{ or } b = -3.
\end{align*}
Since point $A$ is $(1,1),$ $B \neq (1,1)$, so $b = -3.$  Then 
\begin{align*}
B &= (-3,9)\\
\end{align*}

